<br>
<br>
Of course, you have such faith in Bush that you're sure money has nothing whatsoever to do with the invasion of Iraq.  It's all about freedom and democracy. <br>
<br>
To that I say HAHAHAHAHAHAAHHAHAHAHAHAHAH.<br>
<br>
<br>
Here are some actual quotes - history of US Foreign Policy.  I doubt much has changed....<br>
<br>
<br>
1)  General Smedly Butler, after he retired, reconsidering his career for the United States military:<br>
<br>
&quot;I spent 33 years and 4 months in active military service. And during that period I spent most of my time as a high-class muscle man for BIG BUSINESS, for wall street and the bankers.  In short, I was a racketeer, a gangster for capitalism.  Thus, I helped make Mexico and especially Tampico safe for American oil interests in 1914.  I helped make Haiti and Cuba a decent place for the National City Bank Boys to collect revenue in.  I helped in the ranking of half a dozen Central American Republics for the benefit of Wall Street.  I helped purify Nicaragua for the international banking house of Brown Brothers in 1902-1912.  I brought  light to the Dominican Republic for American sugar interests in 1916.   I helped make Honduras right for American fruit companies in 1903.  In China in 1927 I helped see to it that Standard Oil went on it's way unmolested.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
2) World War 1 was a horrific battle among the European colonial powers over how to divide up the world.  When President Woodrow Wilson decided to enter the fray, he told the American people that he was sending troops to Europe to 'make the world safe for democracy.'  Wilson's ambassador to England said rather forthrightly that the USA would declare war on Germany b/c it was... &quot;the only way of maintaining our pre-eminent trade status.&quot;<br>
<br>
General Smedly Butler said in 1934:  <br>
<br>
 &quot;Our boys were sent off to die with beautiful ideals painted in front of them.  No one told them that dollars and cents were the real reason they were marching off to kill and die.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
3) 1941.  Quote from a private memorandum between the Council on Foreign Relations and the State Department:<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;If war aims are stated which seem to be concerned solely with Anglo-American imperialism - they will offer little to people in the rest of the world...The interests of other people should be stressed....This would have  a better propaganda effect.&quot;<br>
<br>
4) Iraq. 1991.  The US State Department declared that MIddle East oil was:  &quot; a stupendous source of stratetic power...one of the greatest prizes in world history.&quot;  And  a Bush advisor said to Time Magazine:  &quot;Even a dolt understands the principle - we need the oil.&quot;<br>
<br>
5) Iran Iraq and the Gulf War.  In the early 1980s Iran was seen as the main threat to US 'interests' in the Gulf, so Washington and its allies encouraged Iraq to invade Iran and provided the Iraqi military with lots of high tech weapons to pound their neighbour with.  After the Iran Iraq war ended in 1988, Washington was worried that the large army it had helped build in Iraq threatened US domination of the region.  Now, it was decided, something had to be done to disarm Iraq.  In fact, there's evidence that the US may have provoked then lured Iraq into invading Kuwait, to have a pretext for US intervention.  The US,Saudi Arabia and Kuwait combined to put severe economic pressure on Iraq, which is the reason Iraq began thinking about an invasion in the first place.  Then, when Saddam Hussein informed the US about his plans, Washington virtually gave him the green light:<br>
<br>
&quot;We have no opinion on your border dispute with Kuwait&quot; <br>
<br>
US Ambassador April Glaspie to Saddam Hussein, July 1990.  To make sure there was NO CONFUSION, she added:  &quot;James Baker has directed our official spokesman to emphasize the instruction.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
6) Profits from the first Gulf War.  Earnings soared 75% at Enron.  Profits rose 68.6% at Amoco.  Texaco Net up 26.5% , Chevron climbs 17.8%.  Mobil's profit jumps 45.6% in Quarter...<br>
<br>
Some 900 billion in Middle Eastern oil profits fill the vaults of Citibank, Chase Manhattan, and other banks in the US, Europe and Japan.<br>
<br>
7)  Propaganda.  General Electric profits from US imperialism.  GE is the country's third largest military contractor. It produces parts for every nuclear weapon in the US arsenal, makes jet engines for military aircraft and makes all kinds of profitable electronic gadgets for the Pentagon.  <br>
<br>
GE also owns NBC.  In 1950, Charles Wilson, chairman of the board of General Electric (whom Truman had just appointed to head of the Office of Defense Mobilisation) spelled out what this work was in a speech to the Newspaper Publishers Association in 1950:<br>
<br>
&quot;If the people were not convinced that the freel world is in Mortal Danger it would be impossible for congress to vote the vast sums now being spent to avert this danger.  With the support of public opinion, as marshalled by the press, we are off to a good start.  It is our job - yours and mine - to keep our people convinced that the only way to keep disaster away from our shores is to build up America's might.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
The boards of directors of the corporations that own the Three networks (GE , Capital cities/ABC and CBS inc) are filled with very wealthy and powerful men.  Some come directly from the White House and the Pentagon. They are:<br>
<br>
General David Jones, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff<br>
Harold Brown, former secretary of defense<br>
William Smith, former US attorney general<br>
Henry Kissinger, former Secretary of State<br>
<br>
Other members of the boards that control the networks are also the directors of some of the biggest banks:  JPMorgan, Chemical Banking,  Chase Manhattan, Citibank.<br>
<br>
Weapons manufacturers:  AT+T, Textron, IBM, Honeywell, ITT Defense, Texon.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Most of the news media available to Americans - about war and peace and everything else - is filtered through the perspective of the corporate news media.  <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
So please, give me a break.  Protecting the world from Iraqi WMDS...saving Iraqis from torture chambers, and whatever excuses you can come up with as to why the invasoin of Iraq was justified.  It's all about money, and your very news media is controlled by the people who stand to make the most money from imperialism, war and 'the rebuilding of Iraq' and any other country the USA chooses to invade.<br>
<br>
<br>
And no, though it may look like it, I am not singling out the USA here.  Whenever a nation *chooses* to go to war, it is most likely about economics and land. It all comes down to economics and you'd have to be pretty naive to believe otherwise.  Human history is full of countries going to war to either improve the economy or grab more land.  And the USA is not any different.<br>
